05956nam a22009615i 9780520969759DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019020046  a97805209697597 a10.1525/97805209697592doi  a(DE-B1597)563073  a(OCoLC)1163878467  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aKF3035b.R668 2020 4aKF3035b.R63 2020 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a340.092aB2231 aRosen, Gary A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAdventures of a Jazz Age Lawyer :bNathan Burkan and the Making of American Popular Culture /cGary A. Rosen. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue: Nathan the Wise -- tPART ONE. Leg Shows and Longhairs -- tPART TWO. A River of Nickels -- tPART THREE. Bending the Firmament -- tPART FOUR. Fleeting, Ephemeral, and Fugitive -- tPART FIVE. Chief Justice of Celluloidia -- tPART SIX. Twenty Days in January 1927 -- tPART SEVEN. The Naked City -- tPART EIGHT. Modern Times -- tAcknowledgments -- tChronology -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAdventures of a Jazz Age Lawyer is the lively story of legal giant Nathan Burkan, whose career encapsulated the coming of age of the institutions, archetypes, and attitudes that define American popular culture. With a client list that included Charlie Chaplin, Al Jolson, Frank Costello, Victor Herbert, Mae West, Gloria Morgan Vanderbilt, Arnold Rothstein, and Samuel Goldwyn, Burkan was "New York's Spotlight Lawyer" for more than three decades. He was one of the principal authors of the epochal Copyright Act of 1909 and the guiding spirit behind the American Society of Composers, Authors, and Publishers (Ascap), which provided the first practical means for songwriters to collect royalties for public performances of their works, revolutionizing the music business and the sound of popular music. While the entertainment world adapted to the disruptive technologies of recorded sound, motion pictures, and broadcasting, Burkan's groundbreaking work laid the legal foundation for the Great American Songbook and the Golden Age of Hollywood, and it continues to influence popular culture today.Gary A. Rosen tells stories of dramatic and uproarious courtroom confrontations, scandalous escapades of the rich and famous, and momentous clashes of powerful political, economic, and cultural forces. Out of these conflicts, the United States emerged as the world's leading exporter of creative energy. Adventures of a Jazz Age Lawyer is an engaging look at the life of Nathan Burkan, a captivating history of entertainment and intellectual property law in the early twentieth century, and a rich source of new discoveries for anyone interested in the spirit of the Jazz Age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCopyrightxArtistic performancezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aCopyrightxMusiczUnited StatesxHistory. 0aCopyrightxPerforming rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPerforming artszUnited Statesy20th centuryxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aal jolson.  aamerican popular culture.  aamerican society of composers authors and publishers.  aarnold rothstein.  aascap.  acareer.  acharlie chaplin.  acopyright act of 1909.  acultural forces.  aeconomic.  afrank costello.  agloria morgan vanderbilt.  alawyer.  alegal giant.  amae west.  anathan burkan.  anew york.  apolitical.  arevolutionizing the music business.  arich and famous.  aroyalties.  asamuel goldwyn.  ascandalous escapades.  asongwriters